  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The entrepreneur visa application involves multiple steps across your home country and Germany. Processing typically takes 1-3 months, though timelines vary by embassy and business complexity. Working with an immigration lawyer significantly improves success rates.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Develop Your Business Plan</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Create a comprehensive business plan (20-40 pages) covering market analysis, financials, your qualifications, and why your business benefits Germany. Consider hiring a German business consultant to ensure it meets local expectations. This is the most critical document.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Gather Supporting Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Collect: valid passport, biometric photos, CV/resume, educational certificates, proof of professional experience, proof of financing (bank statements, investor letters), and health insurance certificate. Some documents need certified German translations and apostilles.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply at German Embassy/Consulate</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Book an appointment at your local German embassy or consulate. Submit your visa application, pay the fee (€75-100), and attend an interview. The embassy forwards your application to Germany for assessment by local authorities.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">IHK and Authority Assessment</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">The Chamber of Commerce (IHK) and local immigration authority (Ausländerbehörde) in your intended German city review your business plan. They assess economic benefit, viability, and your qualifications. This takes 2-8 weeks. They may request additional information.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Visa Decision</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Upon approval, the embassy issues your visa (usually valid 90 days for entry). If rejected, you can appeal or reapply with a stronger application. Common rejection reasons: unclear economic benefit, insufficient financing, weak business plan, or lack of relevant experience.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Enter Germany and Register (Anmeldung)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Enter Germany within your visa validity period. Within 14 days of finding housing, register your address at the local Bürgeramt (citizens' office). This Anmeldung is required before you can proceed with other registrations.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply for Residence Permit</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Book an appointment at the Ausländerbehörde to convert your visa into a residence permit (Aufenthaltstitel). Bring all original documents. You'll receive a provisional permit while the card is produced. The permit is typically valid 1-3 years.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Register Your Business</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Register with the Gewerbeamt (trade office) for trade businesses, or with the Finanzamt (tax office) if you're a freelancer. For GmbH/UG, complete notarization and register with the Handelsregister (commercial register). Open a German business bank account.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Berlin-specific tip:</strong> Berlin's Ausländerbehörde is notoriously backlogged. Appointments can take months to secure. Use early morning appointment slots, consider hiring an immigration lawyer who has contacts, and bring complete documentation to avoid repeat visits. The Berlin Business Office (Berlin Partner) can also assist international entrepreneurs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Real-World Scenarios -->
