  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Submitting a Weak or Generic Business Plan</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">German authorities take business plans seriously. A generic template or vague description of "consulting services" will likely be rejected. Invest time (and potentially money for professional help) in a comprehensive, Germany-specific business plan that clearly demonstrates economic benefit and your qualifications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the IHK Review</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Chamber of Commerce (IHK) assessment is not a rubber stamp. They genuinely evaluate whether your business makes economic sense for Germany. Research similar businesses, understand the competitive landscape, and be prepared to explain why your offering is needed. Consider scheduling a pre-consultation with IHK before applying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Proof of Financing</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While there's no minimum investment, you must prove your business is financially viable. Personal bank statements should show sufficient funds to cover startup costs and living expenses for at least 12 months. Investor commitments should be documented in writing. Don't rely on "I'll figure it out later."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring the Over-45 Pension Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you're over 45, the pension provision requirement is strictly enforced. Prepare comprehensive documentation of retirement savings, pension entitlements, property, and other assets. This isn't about proving wealth—it's about showing you won't need German social benefits in retirement.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing the Wrong City</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Each city's Ausländerbehörde has different approaches and processing times. Berlin is entrepreneur-friendly but severely backlogged. Munich is efficient but more conservative in assessments. Research your target city's approach and timeline. Your business address determines which authority processes your application.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Germany -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Germany</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Germany has one of the world's best healthcare systems, with universal coverage and excellent quality. As an entrepreneur, you have more flexibility in choosing between public and private insurance than employees do. Understanding the system helps you make the right choice.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The German Healthcare System</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">Public System (GKV)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Covers ~87% of population</li>
          <li>• Comprehensive coverage by law</li>
          <li>• All pre-existing conditions covered</li>
          <li>• Family members included free</li>
          <li>• Premium based on income (~15%)</li>
          <li>• Maximum premium ~€900/month</li>
          <li>• Minor out-of-pocket costs</li>
          <li>• Some waiting times for specialists</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Private System (PKV)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>• Covers ~13% of population</li>
          <li>• Premium based on age and health</li>
          <li>• Medical underwriting required</li>
          <li>• Each family member needs own policy</li>
          <li>• Faster access to specialists</li>
          <li>• More doctor choice</li>
          <li>• Private hospital rooms</li>
          <li>• Premium increases with age</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Quality and Access</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Both public and private insurance provide access to excellent care. Key features:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Modern facilities:</strong> German hospitals and clinics have excellent equipment and facilities</li>
      <li><strong>Qualified doctors:</strong> German medical training is rigorous; many doctors speak English</li>
      <li><strong>Comprehensive coverage:</strong> From routine care to complex surgeries and chronic conditions</li>
      <li><strong>Pharmacy network:</strong> Apotheken (pharmacies) are ubiquitous with professional advice</li>
      <li><strong>Emergency care:</strong> Call 112 for emergencies; excellent response times</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist access:</strong> Private patients get faster appointments; public patients may wait weeks</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Major Cities Healthcare Notes</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Berlin</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Large international community</li>
          <li>• Many English-speaking doctors</li>
          <li>• Charité hospital (world-renowned)</li>
          <li>• Good startup health networks</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Munich</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Highest medical density</li>
          <li>• Many private clinics</li>
          <li>• LMU and TU Munich hospitals</li>
          <li>• Excellent specialist access</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Frankfurt</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• International business community</li>
          <li>• English services common</li>
          <li>• Good international insurers</li>
          <li>• Convenient for frequent travelers</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Hamburg</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-neutral-700">
          <li>• Strong hospital network</li>
          <li>• UKE (University Medical Center)</li>
          <li>• Growing international community</li>
          <li>• Good work-life balance focus</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Insurance switching:</strong> Once you choose private insurance in Germany, switching back to public can be difficult (especially after age 55). Consider your long-term plans carefully. If you're unsure, public insurance offers a safe default—you can always switch to private later if circumstances change.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is there a minimum investment amount for Germany's entrepreneur visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Unlike Golden Visa programs in Spain or Portugal, Germany has no fixed minimum investment. Instead, you must demonstrate that your business financing is secured and credible. This could be €10,000 for a freelance business or €500,000+ for a manufacturing facility—it depends entirely on what your business plan requires.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does it take to get permanent residence?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The standard path is 5 years of legal residence. However, successful entrepreneurs can qualify in just 3 years under §21(4) AufenthG if their business has been successful and they meet integration requirements (including basic German). This is one of the fastest PR paths in the EU for entrepreneurs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak German?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          German is not legally required for the initial entrepreneur visa. However, it significantly helps: with authorities, business relationships, and daily life. For permanent residence and citizenship, you'll need to demonstrate German language skills (B1 level). Many successful entrepreneurs start in English-friendly cities like Berlin while learning German.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your spouse and minor children can accompany you or join you later through family reunification. Spouses receive a residence permit with work rights. Children can attend German schools (excellent public education is free). Each family member needs their own health insurance unless covered under public family insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between the entrepreneur visa and EU Blue Card?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The EU Blue Card is for highly skilled employees with a job offer meeting minimum salary requirements (€45,300 or €41,000 for shortage occupations in 2026). The entrepreneur visa is for self-employed individuals starting their own business. If you could work as an employee in a specialized field, the Blue Card offers a simpler path—but if you want to build your own company, the entrepreneur visa is your route.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If your business closes, you must notify the Ausländerbehörde. Your residence permit is tied to self-employment, so you'd need to either start a new business, find employment (different permit required), or leave Germany. However, if you've already obtained permanent residence, losing your business doesn't affect your immigration status.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Germany's entrepreneur visa offers a unique proposition in Europe: access to the EU's largest economy without a minimum investment threshold. Unlike Golden Visas that reward capital, Germany rewards entrepreneurial merit—a viable business plan, relevant experience, and demonstrated economic benefit. This makes it accessible to genuine entrepreneurs who may not have €500,000 to invest in real estate.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-off is a more rigorous, subjective application process. Your success depends on convincing German authorities that your business makes sense for Germany. This requires a strong business plan, clear qualifications, and usually professional help navigating the bureaucracy. The good news: if you can demonstrate genuine business merit, the 3-year path to permanent residence is among Europe's fastest.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Health insurance is mandatory and represents a significant ongoing cost (€150-500/month). You have the freedom to choose between comprehensive public insurance or flexible private options. For entrepreneurs with families or pre-existing conditions, public insurance often makes more sense. For young, healthy individuals who travel frequently, international private insurance provides greater flexibility.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Germany's entrepreneur visa suits genuine business builders who want access to Europe's economic powerhouse without massive capital requirements. Come with a concrete plan, relevant experience, and secured financing—not a vague idea. Budget €150-500/month for mandatory health insurance and consider professional help for the application. If your business succeeds, permanent residence in 3 years is achievable.
      </p>
